  2. (10 pts) Let \(X = (X_{1}, \ldots, X_{n})'\) be the \(n \times p\) data matrix, where \(X_{i} = (X_{i1}, \ldots, X_{ip})'\) is the \(i\)th onservation. Let \(\bar{X} = n^{-1} \sum_{i = 1}^{n} X_{i}\) be the sample mean. Let \(s_{j_1j_2} = n^{-1} \sum_{i = 1}^{n} (X_{ij_1} - \bar{X}_{j_1})(X_{ij_2} - \bar{X}_{j_2})\) be the sample covariance between the \(j_1\)th and \(j_2\)th variables. Let \(S = (s_{j_1j_2})\) be the sample covariance matrix. Show that \[S = \frac{1}{n}X' X - \bar{X}' \bar{X}.\]
    Proof: Let \(A = \frac{1}{n}X' X - \bar{X}' \bar{X}\). The \((j_1,j_2)\)th element of \(A\) is \[ \begin{aligned} a_{j_1,j_2}&=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nX'_{j_1i}X_{ij_2}-\bar{X}_{j1}\bar{X}_{j2}\\ &=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nX_{ij_1}X_{ij_2}-\bar{X}_{j1}\bar{X}_{j2}. \end{aligned} \] On the other hand, \[ \begin{aligned} s_{j_1j_2} &= n^{-1} \sum_{i = 1}^{n} (X_{ij_1} - \bar{X}_{j_1})(X_{ij_2} - \bar{X}_{j_2})\\ &=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nX_{ij_1}X_{ij_2}-\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\bar{X}_{j_1}\bar{X}_{j_2}\\ &=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nX_{ij_1}X_{ij_2}-\bar{X}_{j_1}\bar{X}_{j_2}. \end{aligned} \] Therefore, \(a_{j_1,j_2}=s_{j_1j_2}\), and \(S = \frac{1}{n}X' X - \bar{X}' \bar{X}\).

  3. (10 pts) Find ALL the eigenvalues and their eigenvectors for the following matrices

    • \(\Sigma = \sigma \mathbb{1} \mathbb{1}'\) where \(\mathbb{1} = (1, 1, \ldots, 1)'\) is the \(p\) dimensional vector of 1.

      Solution: Since \(\text{rank}(\Sigma)=1\), we have \(\text{ker}(\Sigma)=p-1\). Thus, \(\lambda=0\) is a root of the characteristic polynomial with multiplicity at least \(p-1\). On the other hand, \(tr(\Sigma)=p\sigma\neq 0\). Thus, \(\Sigma\) has an eigenvalue \(p\sigma\). So \(\Sigma\) has eigenvalue 0 with multiplicity \(p-1\) and eigenvalue \(p\sigma\) with multiplicity 1. The eigenvectors corresponding to 0 solves the equation \(\{\boldsymbol{x}=(x_1,x_2,\dots,x_p)'|x_1+x_2+\dots+x_p=0\}\). One possible solution system would be \[ \left\{\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ -1\\ 0\\ \vdots\\ 0\\ 0\\ \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 0\\ -1\\ \vdots\\ 0\\ 0\\ \end{bmatrix},\dots,\begin{bmatrix} 1\\ 0\\ 0\\ \vdots\\ 0\\ -1\\ \end{bmatrix} \right\}. \] The eigenvector corresponding to \(p\sigma\) can be chosen as \(\mathbb{1}\).

    • \(\Sigma = \mbox{diag}(\sigma_{1}, \ldots, \sigma_{p})\) is a diagonal matrix.

      Solution: We have \(\Sigma=diag\{\sigma_1,\dots,\sigma_p\}=\sigma_1\boldsymbol{e}_1\boldsymbol{e}'_1+\sigma_2\boldsymbol{e}_2\boldsymbol{e}'_2+\dots+\sigma_p\boldsymbol{e}_p\boldsymbol{e}'_p\) where \(\boldsymbol{e}_i\) is the p dimensional vector with the \(i\)th coordinate being 1 and others being 0 for \(i=1,2,\ldots,p\). Since \(\{\boldsymbol{e}_i\}\) are orthogonal, the eigenvalues of \(\Sigma\) are \(\{\sigma_1,\sigma_2,\dots,\sigma_p\}\) and the corresponding eigenvectors are \(\{\boldsymbol{e}_1,\boldsymbol{e}_2,\dots,\boldsymbol{e}_p\}\).

  4. (10 pts) Show that \(\mbox{tr}(AB) = \mbox{tr}(BA)\).
    Proof: Let \(A = (a_{ij})_{p \times q}\) and \(B = (b_{ij})_{q \times p}\). (Note that \(A\) and \(B\) don’t require to be square matrices.) Without loss generality, assume \(p \leq q\). \[\mbox{tr}(AB) = \sum_{i = 1}^{p} \sum_{j = 1}^{q} a_{ij}b_{ji} = \sum_{j = 1}^{q} \sum_{i = 1}^{p} b_{ji}a_{ij} = \mbox{tr}(BA).\]

  5. (10 pts) Given two variables in the data matrix X (say the \(j_1\)th and \(j_2\)th variables). Show that their sample correlation will not change by standardization.
    Proof: Let \(x_{(j_1)}, x_{(j_2)}\) be the \(j_1\)th and \(j_2\)th variables and \(\widetilde{x}_{(j_1)}, \widetilde{x}_{(j_2)}\) be the standarlization of \(x_{(j_1)}\) and \(x_{(j_2)}\). Then, \(\widetilde{x}_{(j_1)}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{s_{j_1j_1}}}(x_{(j_1)}-\bar{x}_{j_1}\mathbb{1})\) and \(\widetilde{x}_{(j_2)}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{s_{j_2j_2}}}(x_{(j_2)}-\bar{x}_{j_2}\mathbb{1})\). The sample correlation between \(\widetilde{x}_{(j_1)}\) and \(\widetilde{x}_{(j_2)}\) is \[ \begin{aligned} \widetilde{r}_{j_1j_2} &=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\widetilde{x}_{ij_1}\widetilde{x}_{ij_2} =\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\frac{x_{ij_1}-\bar{x}_{j_1}}{\sqrt{s_{j_1j_1}}}\frac{x_{ij_2}-\bar{x}_{j_2}}{\sqrt{s_{j_2j_2}}}\\ &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{s_{j_1j_1}}\sqrt{s_{j_2j_2}}}\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(x_{ij_1}-\bar{x}_{j_1})(x_{ij_2}-\bar{x}_{j_2})\\ &=\frac{s_{j_1j_2}}{\sqrt{s_{j_1j_1}}\sqrt{s_{j_2j_2}}} =r_{j_1j_2}. \end{aligned} \]

  6. (15 pts) Given a data matrix \(X\) as in Question 2. Assume the means of the \(p\) variables are zero. Let \(S = \frac{1}{n}X' X\) be the sample covariance matrix. Let \(\lambda_{1} \geq \lambda_{2} \geq \ldots \geq \lambda_{p}\) be the ordered eigenvalues of \(S\). Let \(e_{1}, \ldots, e_{p}\) be their corresponding orthogonal eigenvectors with unit length. In multivariate analysis, we usually want to use the first few eigenvalues and eigenvectors to represent the original data, as a tool of dimension reduction.

    • On one aspect, let \[S_{m} = \lambda_{1}e_{1}e_{1}' + \ldots + \lambda_{m}e_{m}e_{m}'\] be an approximate of \(S\) for \(m < p\). Calculate \(\mbox{tr}\{(S - S_{m})^{2}\}\) and \(\mbox{tr}\{(S - S_{m})^{2}\} / \mbox{tr}(S^{2})\), where \(\mbox{tr}(S^{2})\) can be regarded as the total variation of the data.

      Solution: Note that \(\mbox{tr}\{(S-S_m)^2\} = \mbox{tr}(S^{2}) + \mbox{tr}(S_{m}^{2}) - 2 \mbox{tr} (S S_{m})\), and \(\mbox{tr}(S^{2}) = \sum_{i = 1}^{p} \lambda_{i}^{2}\), \(\mbox{tr}(S^{2}) = \sum_{i = 1}^{m} \lambda_{i}^{2}\). We also have \(\mbox{tr} (S S_{m}) = \mbox{tr}(S_{m}^{2})\) Therefore, \[\frac{\mbox{tr}\{(S-S_m)^2\}}{\mbox{tr}(S^2)} = \frac{\sum_{i=m+1}^p\lambda_i^2}{\sum_{i=1}^p \lambda_i^2}.\]
    • On another aspect, \(\{Xe_{1}, \ldots, Xe_{m}\}\) are the transformed data by the eigenvectors. Calculate the sample covariance \(S_{t}\) of \(\{Xe_{1}, \ldots, Xe_{m}\}\) (regard the sample mean as 0). What is \(\mbox{tr}(S_{t}^{2})\) comparing to \(\mbox{tr}(S^{2})\)?

      Solution: Note that \(\{Xe_1,\dots,Xe_m\}=X(e_1,\dots,e_m)\). This leads to \[ \begin{aligned} S_t&=\frac{1}{n}\left(X(e_1,\dots,e_m)\right)'X(e_1,\dots,e_m)\\ &=\frac{1}{n}\begin{pmatrix} e_1'\\ e_2'\\ \vdots\\ e_m' \end{pmatrix}X'X(e_1,e_2,\dots,e_m)\\ &=\begin{pmatrix} e_1'\\ e_2'\\ \vdots\\ e_m' \end{pmatrix}S(e_1,e_2,\dots,e_m)\\ &=\begin{pmatrix} e_1'\\ e_2'\\ \vdots\\ e_m' \end{pmatrix}(\lambda_1e_1e_1'+\dots+\lambda_pe_pe_p')(e_1,\dots,e_m)\\ &=\begin{pmatrix} \lambda_1e_1'\\ \lambda_2e_2'\\ \vdots\\ \lambda_me_m' \end{pmatrix}(e_1,e_2,\dots,e_m)\\ &=\text{diag}(\lambda_1,\dots,\lambda_m). \end{aligned} \] Therefore, \(\text{tr}(S_t^2)=\sum_{i=1}^m\lambda_i^2=\text{tr}(S_m^2)\).
    • What can you conclude on the dimension reduction by eigenvectors from the above two points?

      Solution: If there is a few leading eigenvalues dominating the summation \(\sum_{i=1}^p \lambda_i^2\), dimension reduction by eigenvectors can preserve most of the total variation of the original data while decrease the dimensions of the variables.

coord_radar <- function (theta = "x", start = 0, direction = 1) 
{
    theta <- match.arg(theta, c("x", "y"))
    r <- if (theta == "x") 
        "y"
    else "x"
    ggproto("CordRadar", CoordPolar, theta = theta, r = r, start = start, 
        direction = sign(direction),
        is_linear = function(coord) TRUE)
}

  1. (20 pts) The 109th US Congress, comprising the Senate and the House of Representatives, was the legislative branch of the US government from January 3, 2005 to January 3, 2007. During this period, 542 bills were voted on by the US Senate. Each of 100 Senators either voted in favor or against or failed to record their vote on each of these bills. Details voting preferences of the 100 senators on these bills is provided in the ‘senate-109.csv’ file available on Canvas homework folder.

    In the ‘senate-109.csv’ file, “1” denotes voting in favor, “-1” denotes voting against while “0” means a vote not recorded. The voting resolutions are in the rows while the votes are the columns. Also,the first row of the file contains their names and states. The file senate-109-party.csv contains the last name and the party ID of the senators.
  • Extract the last names of the senators from ‘senate-109.csv’ file.
  senator = read.csv("senate-109.csv", sep=',', header = TRUE)
  full_name = names(senator)[-c(1,2)] 
  extract.name = function(z){
    m = length(z)
    for (i in m : 1){
      if (nchar(z[i]) >= 3 & z[i] != "III") return(z[i])
    }
  }
  names = unlist(lapply(strsplit(full_name, "[.]"), extract.name))

  • Use Andrews’ curves, display the voting preferences of each senator. Use red for “Republican”, blue for “Democratic” and purple for “Independent”. Comment. Andrews’ curves (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrews_plot) is based on Fourier series to visualize high-dimensional data. Use andrews() function in the andrews package (https://rdrr.io/cran/andrews/man/andrews.html).
   # Andrews' curve by "pracma" package, similar plot can be made by "andrews" package
   #library(pracma)
   #andrew_data = Data %>% select(-name, -partyID) %>% as.matrix()
   #andrewsplot(andrew_data, Data$partyID, style = "cart")
   
   # The following code is from Yudi's solution:
   do.andrews <- function(x,breaks=30) {
  require(reshape2)
  
  t <- seq(-pi, pi, pi/breaks)
  m<-nrow(x)
  n<-ncol(x)
  
  f <- matrix(t,nrow=length(t),ncol=n)
  j <- seq(2,n)
  
  f[,j[j%%2==0]] <- sweep(f[,j[j%%2==0],drop=FALSE],
                          2,
                          j[j%%2==0]/2,
                          `*`)
  
  f[,j[j%%2!=0]] <- sweep(f[,j[j%%2!=0],drop=FALSE],
                          2,
                          j[j%%2!=0]%/%2,
                          `*`)
  f[,j[j%%2==0]] <- sin(f[,j[j%%2==0]])
  f[,j[j%%2!=0]] <- cos(f[,j[j%%2!=0]])
  
  f <- x[,j]%*%t(f[,j])
  f <- f+matrix(x[,1]/2^0.5,nrow=m,ncol=length(t),byrow=F)
  
  res <- melt(f,varnames=c('RowId','AndrewsId'),value.name = 'AndrewsValue')
  res[,'AndrewsId'] <- t[res[,'AndrewsId']]
  
  return(res)
}

Data %>%
  group_by(partyID) %>%
  do({do.andrews(as.matrix(select(., -name, -partyID)))}) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = AndrewsId,y = AndrewsValue,color = partyID,group = interaction(partyID,RowId)))+
  geom_line(size = 0.8) + scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "purple", "red"))


- What is a good measure for the “closeness” between two senetors? Is Pearson correlation an ideal choice? Is the measure you chose a valid distance measure?

Solution: The voting is categorical response. Pearson correlation is not appropriate for categorical variables. Instead, we may use Hamming distance, that is the number of positions at which the corresponding values are different. However, Hamming distance may not satisfy the triagular inequality.
